cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.RO, cs.NE 

This paper deals with predicting boundaries in images and videos, which is a problem in computer vision. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also involves machine learning techniques, which makes cs.LG (Machine Learning) another likely category. The paper also mentions the model's ability to learn about the fate of boundaries and extrapolate motion patterns, which suggests the involvement of artificial intelligence, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) another likely category. The paper also experiments on established real-world video segmentation dataset, which involves robotics and automation, making cs.RO (Robotics) another likely category. Finally, the paper mentions the model's ability to derive a notion of "intuitive physics," which suggests the involvement of neural networks, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) another likely category.
